04759nam a2200697Ia 9780801471537DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1164784959  a(OCoLC)979748013  a97808014715377 a10.7591/97808014715372doi  a(DE-B1597)478665  a(OCoLC)889264476  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0110002bisacsh0481pa820qDE-1011 aThiébaux, Marcelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStag of Love :bThe Chase in Medieval Literature /cMarcelle Thiébaux. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (250 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tI. Literature and the Hunt -- tII. The Chase in Medieval Narrative -- tIII. The Love Chase -- tEpilogue: After Hadamar -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA sport and a military exercise, hunting involved aggressive action with weapons and dogs, and pursuit to the point of combat and killing, for the sake of recreation, food or conquest. The Stag of Love explores the body of erotic metaphor that developed from the hunt together with Ovid's flourishing legacies. While representing a range of human experience, the metaphor finds its dominant expression in the literature of love. As Marcelle Thiébaux demonstrates, the hunt's disciplined violence represented sexual desire, along with strategies and arts for getting love, the joys of love, and love's elevating mystique. The genre gave rise to a lavish imagery of footprints and tracking, arrows, nets, dogs and leashes, wounds, dismemberment and blood, that persisted to Shakespeare's day.Thiébaux opens with an account of a medieval chase and its ceremonies. She introduces hunt manuals that defined and gentrified the sport, in stages from the party's departure to the ferocity of the struggle to the animal's death. These stages adapted readily to narrative structures in the love chase, showing pursuit, confrontation with the beloved, and consummation. In English literature Thiébaux considers Beowulf, Aefric's Life of St. Eustace, Sir Gawain and the Green Knight, and Chaucer. She discusses Aucassin and Nicolete, Chrétien de Troyes' Erec, Gottfried von Strassburg's Tristan, the Nibelungenlied, and Wolfram von Eschenbach's works. The study ends with a scrutiny of newly recovered or little-known narratives of the thirteenth, fourteenth and fifteenth centuries.Originally published in 1974 and now issued in paperback for the first time, The Stag of Love brings to life a theme of perennial interest to medievalists, and to all readers intrigued by the imaginative treatment of love in the Western world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHunting in literature. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aLove in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aOvid, human experience in literature, literature of love, hunting, medieval ceremonies, hunting as a metaphor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147153740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801471537/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EE